Assume a TypeScript node/express project and the following code:
```ts
function routeHandler(req: Request, res: Response){
  try {
    res.send('good')
  } catch (err){
    next|   // here | denotes the caret
  }
}

```
Let's note that at this point `next: NextFunction` is missing from the handler signature.
At this point, when typing `next`, the only available autocomplete suggestion is most probably something else, in my case it is `nextTick`.
As long as `next` remains typed - suggesting `nextTick` is perfectly ok.
But the moment user continues to type `(` - `nextTick` should no longer be offered as an autocomplete option, furthermore, it should not be assumed that user has selected it - which is exactly what is happening.
`next(` !== `nextTick()`
The opening parenthesis should be treated as user's closing the text input and dismissing autocomplete if nothing matched.
Current behavior is very confusing and requires post-massaging of the generated code, I believe there should be a preference setting to control this flow.

